<subSubSection pageId="61" pageNumber="62" type="type">
<paragraph pageId="61" pageNumber="62">Type.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="61" pageNumber="62">
LEBANON, between Hasbey and Rasheiya, 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="61" pageNumber="62">Boissier</emphasis>
s.n. (holotype G, n.v).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="61" pageNumber="62" type="description">
<paragraph pageId="61" pageNumber="62">Description.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="61" pageNumber="62">
Annual herb, mostly branched at base, with decumbent or ascending stems to c. 30 cm, vegetative parts thinly pubescent. Leaves petiolate, 2-4(-5) 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
1.5-3 cm, ovate or reniform, apex rounded, margin entire or undulate, base weakly auriculate, cordate and cuneate onto the petiole; petioles up to 10 cm on basal leaves but mostly 2-3 cm on cauline leaves. Flowers solitary, axillary, pedunculate, becoming congested upwards; bracts resembling small leaves, but sometimes deeply palmately lobed with acute lobes; peduncles 0.5-5 cm, elongating and reflexing in fruit; bracteoles 3-4 mm, filiform to linear-lanceolate; pedicels 0.3-1.5 cm; sepals 3-6 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
3-4 mm, broadly oblong-obovate, prominently mucronate, stiffly hirsute with spreading hairs; corolla 1.5-2(-2.8) cm, pink or pinkish purple, unlobed, midpetaline bands pilose; filaments glandular below; ovary glabrous; style glabrous, divided c. 4 mm above base, stigmas c. 1.5 mm. [
<bibRefCitation author="Sa'ad, F" journalOrPublisher="Bronder Offset, Rotterdam" pageId="210" pageNumber="211" pagination="1 - 287" refId="B314" refString="Sa'ad, F, 1967. The Convolvulus species of the Canary Isles, the Mediterranean region, and the Near and Middle East. Mededelingen van het Botanisch Museum en Herbarium van de Rijksuniversite Utrecht. Bronder Offset, Rotterdam: 1 - 287" title="The Convolvulus species of the Canary Isles, the Mediterranean region, and the Near and Middle East. Mededelingen van het Botanisch Museum en Herbarium van de Rijksuniversite Utrecht" year="1967">
<normalizedToken originalValue="Sa’ad">Sa'ad</normalizedToken>
1967
</bibRefCitation>
: 174; 
<bibRefCitation author="Feinbrun-Dothan, N" journalOrPublisher="The Israel Academy of Sciences and Humanities, Jerusalem" pageId="202" pageNumber="203" pagination="33 - 43" refId="B119" refString="Feinbrun-Dothan, N, 1978. Flora Palaestina volumen 3: Ericaceae to Compositae. The Israel Academy of Sciences and Humanities, Jerusalem: 33 - 43" title="Flora Palaestina volumen 3: Ericaceae to Compositae" year="1978">Feinbrun-Dothan 1978</bibRefCitation>
: plate 57; 
<bibRefCitation author="Tohme, G" journalOrPublisher="National Council for Scientific Research, Beirut" pageId="213" pageNumber="214" pagination="1 - 609" refId="B363" refString="Tohme, G, Tohme, H, 2007. Illustrated Flora of Lebanon. National Council for Scientific Research, Beirut: 1 - 609" title="Illustrated Flora of Lebanon" year="2007">
<normalizedToken originalValue="Tohmé">Tohme</normalizedToken>
and 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Tohmé">Tohme</normalizedToken>
2007
</bibRefCitation>
: 214 (photo); 
<bibRefCitation author="Meikle, RD" journalOrPublisher="Flora of Cyprus" pageId="207" pageNumber="208" pagination="1163 - 1179" refId="B227" refString="Meikle, RD, 1985. . Flora of Cyprus volume 2: 1163 - 1179" volume="volume 2" year="1985">Meikle 1985</bibRefCitation>
: 1173]
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="61" pageNumber="62" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="61" pageNumber="62">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="61" pageNumber="62">
Eastern Mediterranean, apparently especially common in Cyprus: Cyprus (
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="61" pageNumber="62">Davis</emphasis>
2979, 3033); Turkey; Syria (
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="61" pageNumber="62">Hasbani</emphasis>
464, 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="61" pageNumber="62">Barbey</emphasis>
612); Lebanon (
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="61" pageNumber="62">Polunin</emphasis>
5208, 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="61" pageNumber="62">Gombault</emphasis>
4497, 4499); Palestine/Israel (
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="61" pageNumber="62">Davis</emphasis>
4214, 4500, 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="61" pageNumber="62">Eig et al.</emphasis>
276).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="61" pageNumber="62" type="notes">
<paragraph pageId="61" pageNumber="62">Notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="61" pageNumber="62">The retuse, strongly apiculate sepals, reflexed fruiting peduncles and annual habit are distinctive.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="61" pageNumber="62">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="61" pageNumber="62">Species 19-21</emphasis>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="61" pageNumber="62">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Batt., in Pitard, Explor. Sci. Maroc, Bot. 74. 1913. (Pitard" authorityYear="1913" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Convolvulus pitardii" order="Solanales" pageId="61" pageNumber="62" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="pitardii">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="61" pageNumber="62">Convolvulus pitardii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Braun-Blanquet &amp; Maire, Bull. Soc. Hist. Nat. Afrique N. 13: 18. 1922. (Braun-Blanquet and Maire" authorityYear="1922" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Convolvulus glaouorum" order="Solanales" pageId="61" pageNumber="62" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="glaouorum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="61" pageNumber="62">Convolvulus glaouorum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Pau, Bol. Soc. Esp. Hist. Nat. 21: 279. 1921. (Vidal y Lopez" authorityYear="1921" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Convolvulus vidalii" order="Solanales" pageId="61" pageNumber="62" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="vidalii">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="61" pageNumber="62">Convolvulus vidalii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
form a complex of species. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Pau, Bol. Soc. Esp. Hist. Nat. 21: 279. 1921. (Vidal y Lopez" authorityYear="1921" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Convolvulus vidalii" order="Solanales" pageId="61" pageNumber="62" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="vidalii">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="61" pageNumber="62">Convolvulus vidalii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is the most restricted in distribution and the best defined. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Batt., in Pitard, Explor. Sci. Maroc, Bot. 74. 1913. (Pitard" authorityYear="1913" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Convolvulus pitardii" order="Solanales" pageId="61" pageNumber="62" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="pitardii">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="61" pageNumber="62">Convolvulus pitardii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Braun-Blanquet &amp; Maire, Bull. Soc. Hist. Nat. Afrique N. 13: 18. 1922. (Braun-Blanquet and Maire" authorityYear="1922" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Convolvulus glaouorum" order="Solanales" pageId="61" pageNumber="62" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="glaouorum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="61" pageNumber="62">Convolvulus glaouorum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are more widely distributed, their geographical patterning only partially defined with the former mostly in the Eastern Rif and Middle Atlas while the latter is mostly in the High Atlas. Most specimens are easily assigned to one or other species but further study is needed.
</paragraph>
